# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rollback-netcode
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Historically, debates about determinism have involved many philosophical positions and given rise to multiple varieties or interpretations of determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] One topic of debate concerns the scope of determined systems.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Some philosophers have maintained that the entire universe is a single determinate system, while others identify more limited determinate systems.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Another common debate topic is whether determinism and free will can coexist; compatibilism and incompatibilism represent the opposing sides of this debate.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Determinism should not be confused with the self-determination of human actions by reasons, motives, and desires.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Determinism is about interactions which affect cognitive processes in people's lives.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] It concerns the cause and effect of human actions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Cause and result are always bound together in cognitive processes.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] It assumes that if an observer has sufficient information about an object or human being, then such an observer might be able to predict every consequent move of that object or human being.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Determinism rarely requires that perfect prediction be practically possible.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Causal determinism posits that every event results from preceding events and natural laws, while nomological determinism emphasizes the predictability of the future from past and present states.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Necessitarianism claims only one possible world exists, and predeterminism suggests events are fixed in advance, sometimes biologically or genetically.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Fatalism and theological determinism attribute outcomes to fate or divine omniscience, whereas adequate determinism and interpretations of quantum mechanics explore probabilistic or emergent constraints on macroscopic phenomena.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Philosophical varieties extend to human behavior, including biological, psychological, social, and cultural determinism, as well as structural determinism, which highlights systemic constraints.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Historically, determinism appears in both Western traditions, from the Presocratics and Stoics to Newtonian mechanics, and Eastern philosophy, including karma, Ājīvika fatalism, and Buddhist dependent origination.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Modern science recognizes deterministic models in classical physics and complex generative processes, while quantum mechanics introduces probabilistic and debated interpretations.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Causal determinism proposes that there is an unbroken chain of prior occurrences stretching back to the origin of the universe.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The relation between events and the origin of the universe may not be specified.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Causal determinists believe that there is nothing in the universe that has no cause or is self-caused.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Causal determinism has also been considered more generally as the idea that everything that happens and exists is caused by antecedent conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In the case of nomological determinism, these conditions are considered events also, implying that the future is determined completely by preceding events—a combination of prior states of the universe and the laws of nature.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] These conditions can also be considered metaphysical in origin (such as in the case of theological determinism).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Nomological determinism is the most common form of causal determinism and is generally synonymous with physical determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This is the notion that the past and the present dictate the future entirely and necessarily by rigid natural laws and that every occurrence inevitably results from prior events.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Nomological determinism is sometimes illustrated by the thought experiment of Laplace's demon.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Laplace posited that an omniscient observer, knowing with infinite precision all the positions and velocities of every particle in the universe, could predict the future entirely.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Ernest Nagel viewed determinism in terms of a physical state, declaring a theory to be deterministic if it predicts a state at other times uniquely from values at one given time.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Necessitarianism is a metaphysical principle that denies all mere possibility and maintains that there is only one possible way for the world to exist.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Leucippus claimed there are no uncaused events and that everything occurs for a reason and by necessity.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Predeterminism is the idea that all events are determined in advance.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The concept is often argued by invoking causal determinism, implying that there is an unbroken chain of prior occurrences stretching back to the origin of the universe.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In the case of predeterminism, this chain of events has been pre-established, and human actions cannot interfere with the outcomes of this pre-established chain.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Predeterminism can be categorized as a specific type of determinism when it is used to mean pre-established causal determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] It can also be used interchangeably with causal determinism—in the context of its capacity to determine future events.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, predeterminism is often considered as independent of causal determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The term *predeterminism* is also frequently used in the context of biology and heredity, in which case it represents a form of biological determinism, sometimes called *genetic determinism*.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Biological determinism is the idea that all human behaviors, beliefs, and desires are fixed by human genetic nature.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Friedrich Nietzsche explained that human beings are "determined" by their bodies and are subject to its passions, impulses, and instincts.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Fatalism is normally distinguished from determinism, as a form of teleological determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Fatalism is the idea that everything is fated to happen, resulting in humans having no control over their future.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Fate has arbitrary power, and does not necessarily follow any causal or deterministic laws.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Types of fatalism include hard theological determinism and the idea of predestination, where there is a God who determines all that humans will do.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This may be accomplished through either foreknowledge of their actions, achieved through omniscience or by predetermining their actions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Theological determinism is a form of determinism that holds that all events that happen are either preordained (i.e., predestined) to happen by a monotheistic deity, or are destined to occur given its omniscience.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Two forms of theological determinism exist, referred to as *strong* and *weak* theological determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Weak theological determinism is based on the concept of divine foreknowledge—"because God's omniscience is perfect, what God knows about the future will inevitably happen, which means, consequently, that the future is already fixed." There exist slight variations on this categorization, however.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] With respect to free will, "theological determinism is the thesis that God exists and has infallible knowledge of all true propositions including propositions about our future actions", more minimal criteria designed to encapsulate all forms of theological determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Theological determinism can also be seen as a form of causal determinism, in which the antecedent conditions are the nature and will of God.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Some have asserted that Augustine of Hippo introduced theological determinism into Christianity in 412 CE, whereas all prior Christian authors supported free will against Stoic and Gnostic determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, there are many Biblical passages that seem to support the idea of some kind of theological determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Adequate determinism is the idea, because of quantum decoherence, that quantum indeterminacy can be ignored for most macroscopic events.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Random quantum events "average out" in the limit of large numbers of particles (where the laws of quantum mechanics asymptotically approach the laws of classical mechanics).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] While there are specific examples of these random events magnified to macro levels, such as Geiger counters, they are still insignificant in the context of free will.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Stephen Hawking explained that the microscopic world of quantum mechanics is one of determined probabilities.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] That is, nature is not governed by laws that determine the future with certainty but by laws that determine the probability of various futures.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics accepts the linear causal sets of sequential events with adequate consistency yet also suggests constant forking of causal chains that can in principle be globally deterministic.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Meaning the causal set of events leading to the present are all valid yet appear as a singular linear time stream within a much broader unseen conic probability field of other outcomes that "split off" from the locally observed timeline.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Under this model causal sets are still "consistent" yet not exclusive to singular iterated outcomes.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The interpretation sidesteps the exclusive retrospective causal chain problem of "could not have done otherwise" by suggesting "the other outcome does exist" in a set of parallel states of the universe that (in one version) split off in any interacting event.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This interpretation is sometimes described with the example of agent-based choices.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Although some of the above forms of determinism concern human behaviors and cognition, others frame themselves as an answer to the debate on nature and nurture.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] They will suggest that one factor will entirely determine behavior.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] As scientific understanding has grown, however, the strongest versions of these theories have been widely rejected as a single-cause fallacy.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In other words, the modern deterministic theories attempt to explain how the interaction of both nature *and* nurture is entirely predictable.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The concept of heritability has been helpful in making this distinction.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Other deterministic theories actually seek only to highlight the importance of a particular factor in predicting the future.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] These theories often use the factor as a sort of guide or constraint on the future.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] They need not suppose that complete knowledge of that one factor would allow the making of perfect predictions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Structural determinism is the philosophical view that actions, events, and processes are predicated on and determined by structural factors.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Given any particular structure or set of estimable components, it is a concept that emphasizes rational and predictable outcomes.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Chilean biologists Humberto Maturana and Francisco Varela popularized the notion, writing that a living system's general order is maintained via a circular process of ongoing self-referral, and thus its organization and structure defines the changes it undergoes.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] According to the authors, a system can undergo changes of state (alteration of structure without loss of identity) or disintegrations (alteration of structure with loss of identity).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Such changes or disintegrations are not ascertained by the elements of the disturbing agent, as each disturbance will only trigger responses in the respective system, which in turn, are determined by each system's own structure.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] On an individualistic level, what this means is that human beings as free and independent entities are triggered to react by external stimuli or change in circumstance.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, their own internal state and existing physical and mental capacities determine their responses to those triggers.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] For example, the concept has been applied to the politics of race in the United States of America and other Western countries such as the United Kingdom and Australia, with structural determinists lamenting structural factors for the prevalence of racism in these countries.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Additionally, Marxists have conceptualized the writings of Karl Marx within the context of structural determinism as well.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] For example, Louis Althusser, a structural Marxist, argued that the state, in its political, economic, and legal structures, reproduces the discourse of capitalism, in turn, allowing for the burgeoning of capitalistic structures.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Proponents of the notion highlight the usefulness of structural determinism to study complicated issues related to race and gender, as it highlights often gilded structural conditions that block meaningful change.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Critics call it too rigid, reductionist and inflexible.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Additionally, they also criticize the notion for overemphasizing deterministic forces such as structure over the role of human agency and the ability of the people to act.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] These critics argue that politicians, academics, and social activists have the capability to bring about significant change despite stringent structural conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Philosophers have debated both the truth of determinism, and the truth of free will.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This creates the four possible positions in the figure.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Compatibilism refers to the view that free will is, in some sense, compatible with determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The three incompatibilist positions deny this possibility.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The hard incompatibilists hold that free will is incompatible with both determinism and indeterminism, the libertarians that determinism does not hold, and free will might exist, and the hard determinists that determinism does hold and free will does not exist.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The Dutch philosopher Baruch Spinoza was a determinist thinker, and argued that human freedom can be achieved through knowledge of the causes that determine desire and affections.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] He defined human servitude as the state of bondage of anyone who is aware of their own desires, but ignorant of the causes that determined them.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, the free or virtuous person becomes capable, through reason and knowledge, to be genuinely free, even as they are being "determined".
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] For the Dutch philosopher, acting out of one's own internal necessity is genuine freedom while being driven by exterior determinations is akin to bondage.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Spinoza's thoughts on human servitude and liberty are respectively detailed in the fourth and fifth volumes of his work *Ethics*.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The standard argument against free will, according to philosopher J.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Smart, focuses on the implications of determinism for free will.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] He suggests free will is denied whether determinism is true or not.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] He says that if determinism is true, all actions are predicted and no one is assumed to be free; however, if determinism is false, all actions are presumed to be random and as such no one seems free because they have no part in controlling what happens.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Some determinists argue that materialism does not present a complete understanding of the universe, because while it can describe determinate interactions among material things, it ignores the minds or souls of conscious beings.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Another topic of debate is the implication that determinism has on morality.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] That something else should have been done instead implies that there was something else to do.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] That there was something else to do, implies that something else could have been done.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] That something else could have been done implies that there is free will.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] If there is no free will to have done other than *X* we cannot make the moral judgment that *X* should not have been done.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In contrast to such views, philosopher Harry Frankfurt challenged the "principle of alternate possibilities", which states that a person is morally responsible for an action only if they could have done otherwise.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Against this principle, Frankfurt proposes cases in which an individual appears morally responsible even though alternative courses of action are not genuinely available.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In his examples, an external agent (referred to as Black) has the capacity to monitor an individual’s decision-making and stands ready to intervene, for instance by altering the individual’s mental processes, to ensure a particular decision if the individual were about to choose otherwise.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, in the scenario Frankfurt describes, this intervention never occurs because the individual (Jones) independently makes the same decision.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In such cases, although Jones could not have done otherwise because intervention would have occurred if he had tried to choose differently, Frankfurt contends that this lack of alternatives plays no role in bringing about the action and therefore does not undermine moral responsibility.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] These Frankfurt-style cases have been influential in compatibilist accounts of free will, as they suggest that moral responsibility may not depend on the availability of alternative possibilities.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Strawson has argued that the debate over determinism and moral responsibility should be understood in terms of ordinary interpersonal practices rather than resolved solely by appeal to abstract metaphysical conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] These include attitudes such as resentment, gratitude, and forgiveness, which are natural human responses to the perceived good or ill will of others toward oneself or others, as expressed in their actions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Strawson argues that these attitudes, along with their more general or “vicarious” forms directed toward the treatment of others, underlie moral practices and concepts.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] He contrasts “participant” attitudes with the “objective attitude”, in which individuals are regarded as objects of management or treatment rather than as participants in interpersonal relationships.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Such a stance is typically adopted in particular cases involving abnormality or incapacity, rather than as a result of any general belief about the truth of determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] He contends that it is not psychologically possible for human beings to abandon participant attitudes altogether in favor of a wholly objective stance, even if determinism were true.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] On this account, moral responsibility is grounded in the structure of interpersonal relationships and reactive attitudes, and is therefore not undermined by determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Determinism was developed by the Greek philosophers during the 7th and 6th centuries BCE by the Pre-socratic philosophers Heraclitus and Leucippus, later Aristotle, and mainly by the Stoics.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Mecca Chiesa notes that the probabilistic or selectionistic determinism of B.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Skinner comprised a wholly separate conception of determinism that was not mechanistic at all.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Mechanistic determinism assumes that every event has an unbroken chain of prior occurrences, but a selectionistic or probabilistic model does not.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In the West, some elements of determinism have been expressed in Greece from the 6th century BCE by the Presocratics Heraclitus and Leucippus.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The first notions of determinism appears to originate with the Stoics, as part of their theory of universal causal determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The writings of Epictetus as well as middle Platonist and early Christian thought were instrumental in this development.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Jewish philosopher Moses Maimonides said of the deterministic implications of an omniscient god: "Does God know or does He not know that a certain individual will be good or bad?
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Determinism in the West is often associated with Newtonian mechanics/physics, which depicts the physical matter of the universe as operating according to a set of fixed laws.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The "billiard ball" hypothesis, a product of Newtonian physics, argues that once the initial conditions of the universe have been established, the rest of the history of the universe follows inevitably.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] If it were actually possible to have complete knowledge of physical matter and all of the laws governing that matter at any one time, then it would be theoretically possible to compute the time and place of every event that will ever occur (*Laplace's demon*).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In this sense, the basic particles of the universe operate in the same fashion as the rolling balls on a billiard table, moving and striking each other in predictable ways to produce predictable results.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Whether or not it is all-encompassing in so doing, Newtonian mechanics deals only with caused events; for example, if an object begins in a known position and is hit dead on by an object with some known velocity, then it will be pushed straight toward another predictable point.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] If it goes somewhere else, the Newtonians argue, one must question one's measurements of the original position of the object, the exact direction of the striking object, gravitational or other fields that were inadvertently ignored, etc.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Then, they maintain, repeated experiments and improvements in accuracy will always bring one's observations closer to the theoretically predicted results.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] When dealing with situations on an ordinary human scale, Newtonian physics has been successful.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] But it fails as velocities become some substantial fraction of the speed of light and when interactions at the atomic scale are studied.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Before the discovery of quantum effects and other challenges to Newtonian physics, "uncertainty" was always a term that applied to the accuracy of human knowledge about causes and effects, and not to the causes and effects themselves.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Newtonian mechanics, as well as any following physical theories, are results of observations and experiments, and so they describe "how it all works" within a tolerance.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, old western scientists believed if there are any logical connections found between an observed cause and effect, there must be also some absolute natural laws behind.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Belief in perfect natural laws driving everything, instead of just describing what we should expect, led to searching for a set of universal simple laws that rule the world.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This movement significantly encouraged deterministic views in Western philosophy, as well as the related theological views of classical pantheism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Throughout history, the belief that the entire universe is a deterministic system subject to the will of fate or destiny has been articulated in both Eastern and Western religions, philosophy, music, and literature.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Accordingly, they shaped their entire lives in accordance with their interpretations of astral configurations and phenomena.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In the *I Ching* and philosophical Taoism, the ebb and flow of favorable and unfavorable conditions suggests the path of least resistance is effortless (*see*: Wu wei).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In the philosophical schools of the Indian Subcontinent, the concept of *karma* deals with similar philosophical issues to the Western concept of determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Karma is understood as a spiritual mechanism which causes the eternal cycle of birth, death, and rebirth (*saṃsāra*).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Karma, either positive or negative, accumulates according to an individual's actions throughout their life, and at their death determines the nature of their next life in the cycle of Saṃsāra.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Most major religions originating in India hold this belief to some degree, most notably Hinduism, Jainism, Sikhism, and Buddhism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The views on the interaction of karma and free will are numerous, and diverge from each other.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] For example, in Sikhism, god's grace, gained through worship, can erase one's karmic debts, a belief which reconciles the principle of karma with a monotheistic god one must freely choose to worship.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Jainists believe in compatibilism, in which the cycle of Saṃsara is a completely mechanistic process, occurring without any divine intervention.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The Jains hold an atomic view of reality, in which particles of karma form the fundamental microscopic building material of the universe.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The oldest descriptions of the Ājīvika fatalists and their founder Gosāla can be found both in the Buddhist and Jaina scriptures of ancient India.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Buddhist philosophy contains several concepts which some scholars describe as deterministic to various levels.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, the direct analysis of Buddhist metaphysics through the lens of determinism is difficult, due to the differences between European and Buddhist traditions of thought.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In other words, righteous or unrighteous actions in one life will necessarily cause good or bad responses in another future life or more lives.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The early Buddhist texts and later Tibetan Buddhist scriptures associate dependent arising with the fundamental Buddhist doctrines of emptiness (*śūnyatā*) and non-self (*anattā*).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Another Buddhist concept which many scholars perceive to be deterministic is the doctrine of non-self (*anattā*).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Sentient beings are composed of the five aggregates of existence (*skandha*): matter, sensation, perception, mental formations, and consciousness.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Some Western scholars argue that the concept of non-self necessarily disproves the ideas of free will and moral responsibility.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] If there is no autonomous self, in this view, and all events are necessarily and unchangeably caused by others, then no type of autonomy can be said to exist, moral or otherwise.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] However, other scholars disagree, claiming that the Buddhist conception of the universe allows for a form of compatibilism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Although it was once thought by scientists that any indeterminism in quantum mechanics occurred at too small a scale to influence biological or neurological systems, there is indication that nervous systems are influenced by quantum indeterminism due to chaos theory.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] It is unclear what implications this has for the problem of free will given various possible reactions to the problem in the first place.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Many biologists do not grant determinism: Christof Koch, for instance, argues against it, and in favour of libertarian free will, by making arguments based on generative processes (emergence).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Other proponents of emergentist or generative philosophy, cognitive sciences, and evolutionary psychology, argue that a certain form of determinism (not necessarily causal) is true.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] They suggest instead that an illusion of free will is experienced due to the generation of infinite behaviour from the interaction of finite-deterministic set of rules and parameters.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Thus the unpredictability of the emerging behaviour from deterministic processes leads to a perception of free will, even though free will as an ontological entity does not exist.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] As an illustration, the strategy board-games chess and Go have rigorous rules in which no information (such as cards' face-values) is hidden from either player and no random events (such as dice-rolling) happen within the game.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Yet, chess and especially Go with its extremely simple deterministic rules, can still have an extremely large number of unpredictable moves.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] When chess is simplified to 7 or fewer pieces, however, endgame tables are available that dictate which moves to play to achieve a perfect game.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This implies that, given a less complex environment (with the original 32 pieces reduced to 7 or fewer pieces), a perfectly predictable game of chess is possible.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In this scenario, the winning player can announce that a checkmate will happen within a given number of moves, assuming a perfect defense by the losing player, or fewer moves if the defending player chooses sub-optimal moves as the game progresses into its inevitable, predicted conclusion.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] By this analogy, it is suggested, the experience of free will emerges from the interaction of finite rules and deterministic parameters that generate nearly infinite and practically unpredictable behavioural responses.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In theory, if all these events could be accounted for, and there were a known way to evaluate these events, the seemingly unpredictable behaviour would become predictable.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Another hands-on example of generative processes is John Horton Conway's playable Game of Life.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Certain philosophers of science argue that, while causal determinism (in which everything including the brain/mind is subject to the laws of causality) is compatible with minds capable of science, fatalism and predestination is not.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Many mathematical models of physical systems are deterministic.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This is true of most models involving differential equations (notably, those measuring rate of change over time).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Mathematical models that are not deterministic because they involve randomness are called stochastic.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Because of sensitive dependence on initial conditions, some deterministic models may appear to behave nondeterministically; in such cases, a deterministic interpretation of the model may not be useful due to numerical instability and a finite amount of precision in measurement.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Such considerations can motivate the consideration of a stochastic model even though the underlying system is governed by deterministic equations.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Since the beginning of the 20th century, quantum mechanics—the physics of the extremely small—has revealed previously concealed aspects of events.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Before that, Newtonian physics—the physics of everyday life—dominated.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Taken in isolation (rather than as an approximation to quantum mechanics), Newtonian physics depicts a universe in which objects move in perfectly determined ways.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] At the scale where humans exist and interact with the universe, Newtonian mechanics remain useful, and make relatively accurate predictions (e.g. calculating the trajectory of a bullet).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] But whereas in theory, absolute knowledge of the forces accelerating a bullet would produce an absolutely accurate prediction of its path, modern quantum mechanics casts reasonable doubt on this main thesis of determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This doubt takes radically different forms.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The observed results of quantum mechanics are random but various interpretations of quantum mechanics make different assumptions about determinism which cannot be distinguished experimentally.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The standard interpretation widely used by physicists is not deterministic, but the other interpretations have been devised which are deterministic.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Quantum mechanics is the product of a careful application of the scientific method, logic and empiricism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Through a large number of careful experiments physicists developed a rather unintuitive mental model: A particle's path cannot be specified in from its quantum description.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] "Path" is a classical, practical attribute in everyday life, but one that quantum particles do not possess.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Quantum mechanics attributes probability to all possible paths and asserts the only one outcome will be observed.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The randomness in quantum mechanics derives from the quantum aspect of the model.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Different experimental results are obtained for each individual quanta.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] As Stephen Hawking explains, the result is not traditional determinism, but rather determined probabilities.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] As far as the thesis of determinism is concerned, these probabilities, at least, are quite determined.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] On the topic of predictable probabilities, the double-slit experiments are a popular example.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Photons are fired one-by-one through a double-slit apparatus at a distant screen.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] They do not arrive at any single point, nor even the two points lined up with the slits (the way it might be expected of bullets fired by a fixed gun at a distant target).
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Instead, the photons arrive in varying concentrations and times across the screen, and only the final distribution of photons can be predicted.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In that sense the behavior of light in this apparatus is predictable, but there is no way to predict where or when in the resulting interference pattern any single photon will make its contribution.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Some (including Albert Einstein) have argued that the inability to predict any more than probabilities is simply due to ignorance.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The idea is that, beyond the conditions and laws can be observed or deduced, there are also hidden factors or "hidden variables" that determine *absolutely* in which order photons reach the detector screen.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] They argue that the course of the universe is absolutely determined, but that humans are screened from knowledge of the determinative factors.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] So, they say, it only *appears* that things proceed in a probabilistically way.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] John Stewart Bell analyzed Einstein's work in his famous Bell's theorem, which demonstrates that quantum mechanics can make statistical predictions that would be violated if local hidden variables really existed.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Many experiments have verified the quantum predictions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Bell's theorem only applies to local hidden variables.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Quantum mechanics can be formulated with non-local hidden variables to achieve a deterministic theory that is in agreement with experiment.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] An example is the Bohm interpretation of quantum mechanics.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Bohm's Interpretation, though, violates special relativity and it is highly controversial whether or not it can be reconciled without giving up on determinism.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The many-worlds interpretation focuses on the deterministic nature of the Schrodinger's equation.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] For any closed system, including the entire universe, the wavefunction solutions to this equation evolve deterministically.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] The apparent randomness of observations corresponds to branching of the wavefunction, with one world for each possible outcome.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Another foundational assumption to quantum mechanics is that of free will, which has been argued to be foundational to the scientific method as a whole.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Bell acknowledged that abandoning this assumption would both allow for the maintenance of determinism as well as locality.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] This perspective is known as superdeterminism, and is defended by some physicists such as Sabine Hossenfelder and Tim Palmer.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] More advanced variations on these arguments include quantum contextuality, by Bell, Simon B.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Kochen and Ernst Specker, which argues that hidden variable theories cannot be "sensible", meaning that the values of the hidden variables inherently depend on the devices used to measure them.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] In his 1939 address "The Relation between Mathematics and Physics", Paul Dirac pointed out that purely deterministic classical mechanics cannot explain the cosmological origins of the universe; today the early universe is modeled quantum mechanically.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Nevertheless, the question of determinism in modern physics remains debated.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] On one hand, Albert Einstein's theory of relativity, which represents an advancement over Newtonian mechanics, is based on a deterministic framework.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] On the other hand, Einstein himself resisted the indeterministic view of quantum mechanics, as evidenced by his famous debates with Niels Bohr, which continued until his death.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Moreover, chaos theory highlights that even within a deterministic framework, the ability to precisely predict the evolution of a system is often limited.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] A deterministic system may appear random: two apparently identical starting points can result in vastly different results.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Such dynamical systems are sensitive to initial conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Even if the universe followed a strict deterministic order, the human capacity to predict every event and comprehend all underlying causes would still be constrained this kind of sensitivity.
[src:rollback-netcode/determinism] Adequate determinism (see Varieties, above) is the reason that Stephen Hawking called libertarian free will "just an illusion".
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] In computer science, a **deterministic algorithm** is an algorithm that, given a particular input, will always produce the same output, with the underlying machine always passing through the same sequence of states.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Deterministic algorithms are by far the most studied and familiar kind of algorithm, as well as one of the most practical, since they can be run on real machines efficiently.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Formally, a deterministic algorithm computes a mathematical function; a function has a unique value for any input in its domain, and the algorithm is a process that produces this particular value as output.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Deterministic algorithms can be defined in terms of a state machine: a *state* describes what a machine is doing at a particular instant in time.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] State machines pass in a discrete manner from one state to another.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Just after we enter the input, the machine is in its *initial state* or *start state*.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] If the machine is deterministic, this means that from this point onwards, its current state determines what its next state will be; its course through the set of states is predetermined.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Note that a machine can be deterministic and still never stop or finish, and therefore fail to deliver a result.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Examples of particular abstract machines which are deterministic include the deterministic Turing machine and deterministic finite automaton.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Although real programs are rarely purely deterministic, it is easier for humans as well as other programs to reason about programs that are.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] For this reason, most programming languages and especially functional programming languages make an effort to prevent the above events from happening except under controlled conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] The prevalence of multi-core processors has resulted in a surge of interest in determinism in parallel programming and challenges of non-determinism have been well documented.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] A number of tools to help deal with the challenges have been proposed to deal with deadlocks and race conditions.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] It is advantageous, in some cases, for a program to exhibit nondeterministic behavior.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] The behavior of a card shuffling program used in a game of blackjack, for example, should not be predictable by players — even if the source code of the program is visible.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] The use of a pseudorandom number generator is often not sufficient to ensure that players are unable to predict the outcome of a shuffle.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] These problems can be avoided, in part, through the use of a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator, but it is still necessary for an unpredictable random seed to be used to initialize the generator.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] For this purpose, a source of nondeterminism is required, such as that provided by a hardware random number generator.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] Note that a negative answer to the P=NP problem would not imply that programs with nondeterministic output are theoretically more powerful than those with deterministic output.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] The complexity class NP (complexity) can be defined without any reference to nondeterminism using the verifier-based definition.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] The mercury logic-functional programming language establishes different determinism categories for predicate modes as explained in the reference.
[src:rollback-netcode/deterministic-algorithm] In Java, the *null* reference value may represent an unsuccessful (out-of-domain) result.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Before its creation, GGPO creator Tony Cannon was completely dissatisfied with the 2006 Xbox 360 re-release of *Street Fighter II: Hyper Fighting* after experiencing its criticized online capabilities.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] As a reaction to its service, Cannon began development on GGPO and released the first version in late 2006.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Cannon later demonstrated GGPO to Capcom, and it was positively received.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] The downloadable GGPO client supported many games from Capcom and SNK, including *Super Street Fighter II Turbo*, *The King of Fighters 2002*, and Metal Slug X through the use of a built-in emulator.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Video game companies have also implemented a licensed version of GGPO.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Games using it include *Skullgirls* and *Street Fighter III: 3rd Strike Online Edition*.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] On October 9, 2019, Cannon announced on his Twitter account that GGPO was now open source and available under the MIT License.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] GGPO uses a netcode technique called "rollback".
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Rather than waiting for input to be received from other players before simulating the next frame, GGPO predicts the inputs they will send and simulates the next frame without delay using that assumption.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] When other players’ inputs arrive, if any input didn't match the prediction, GGPO rolls back the state of the game to the last correct state, then replays all players’ revised inputs back until the current frame.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] The hope is that the predictions will be correct most of the time, allowing smooth play with minimal sudden changes to the game state.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] The system in itself is highly similar to client-side prediction, but applied to a peer-to-peer setup.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] The client program can allow players to manually adjust native input delay in high-ping situations, either creating a possibly-jerky yet accurate representation or a smoother game with input delay.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] GGPO was originally bundled with a client which enabled users to play supported games online with other players.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] A matchmaking system allowed players to request challenges from other users, while non-participants could spectate the match and chat.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] Once a challenge initiated, the match ran a ROM through its prepackaged emulator, FinalBurn Alpha.
[src:rollback-netcode/ggpo] This client was discontinued, and superseded by other clients which make use of GGPO's networking middleware, such as Fightcade or RedGGPO.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:rollback-netcode/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Due to multiplayer games allowing players to interact with other individuals, they provide an element of social communication absent from single-player games.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The history of multiplayer video games extends over several decades, tracing back to the emergence of electronic gaming in the mid-20th century.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] One of the earliest instances of multiplayer interaction was witnessed with the development of *Spacewar!* in 1962 for the DEC PDP-1 computer by Steve Russell and colleagues at the MIT.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, multiplayer gaming gained momentum within the arcade scene with classics like *Pong* and *Tank*.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The transition to home gaming consoles in the 1980s further popularized multiplayer gaming.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Titles like *Super Mario Bros.* for the NES and *Golden Axe* for the Sega Genesis introduced cooperative and competitive gameplay.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Additionally, LAN gaming emerged in the late 1980s, enabling players to connect multiple computers for multiplayer gameplay, popularized by titles like *Doom* and *Warcraft: Orcs & Humans*.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Players can also play together in the same room using splitscreen.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Some of the earliest video games were two-player games, including early sports games (such as 1958's *Tennis For Two* and 1972's *Pong*), early shooter games such as *Spacewar!* (1962) and early racing video games such as *Astro Race* (1973).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The first examples of multiplayer real-time games were developed on the PLATO system about 1973.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Multi-user games developed on this system included 1973's Empire and 1974's Spasim; the latter was an early first-person shooter.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Other early video games included turn-based multiplayer modes, popular in tabletop arcade machines.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In such games, play is alternated at some point (often after the loss of a life).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] All players' scores are often displayed onscreen so players can see their relative standing.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Danielle Bunten Berry created some of the first multiplayer video games, such as her debut, *Wheeler Dealers* (1978) and her most notable work, *M.U.L.E.* (1983).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Kemeny wrote in 1972 that software running on the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System (DTSS) had recently gained the ability to support multiple simultaneous users, and that games were the first use of the functionality.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] DTSS's popular American football game, he said, now supported head-to-head play by two humans.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The university's computer system had hundreds of terminals, connected (via serial lines) through cluster PDP-11s for student, teacher, and staff access.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The games had a program running on each terminal (for each player), sharing a segment of shared memory (known as the "high segment" in the OS TOPS-10).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The games became popular, and the university often banned them because of their RAM use.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] STAR was based on 1974's single-user, turn-oriented BASIC program STAR, written by Michael O'Shaughnessy at UNH.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Wasserman and Stryker in 1980 described in *BYTE* how to network two Commodore PET computers with a cable.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Their article includes a type-in, two-player Hangman, and describes the authors' more-sophisticated *Flash Attack*.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] SuperSet Software's *Snipes* (1981) uses networking technology that would become Novell NetWare.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Digital Equipment Corporation distributed another multi-user version of *Star Trek*, Decwar, without real-time screen updating; it was widely distributed to universities with DECsystem-10s.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In 1981 Cliff Zimmerman wrote an homage to *Star Trek* in MACRO-10 for DECsystem-10s and -20s using VT100-series graphics.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] "VTtrek" pitted four Federation players against four Klingons in a three-dimensional universe.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer gaming modes are known as "netplay".
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The first popular video-game title with a Local Area Network(LAN) version, 1991's Spectre for the Apple Macintosh, featured AppleTalk support for up to eight players.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Spectre's popularity was partially attributed to the display of a player's name above their cybertank.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] There followed 1993's Doom, whose first network version allowed four simultaneous players.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-email multiplayer games use email to communicate between computers.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Other turn-based variations not requiring players to be online simultaneously are Play-by-post gaming and Play-by-Internet.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Some online games are "massively multiplayer", with many players participating simultaneously.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Two massively multiplayer genres are MMORPG (such as *World of Warcraft* or *EverQuest*) and MMORTS.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] First-person shooters have become popular multiplayer games; *Battlefield 1942* and *Counter-Strike* have little (or no) single-player gameplay.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Developer and gaming site OMGPOP's library included multiplayer Flash games for the casual player until it was shut down in 2013.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Some networked multiplayer games, including MUDs and massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) such as RuneScape, omit a single-player mode.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The largest MMO in 2008 was *World of Warcraft*, with over 10 million registered players worldwide.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] *World of Warcraft* would hit its peak at 12 million players two years later in 2010, and in 2023 earned the Guinness World Record for best selling MMO video game.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This category of games requires multiple machines to connect via the Internet; before the Internet became popular, MUDs were played on time-sharing computer systems and games like *Doom* were played on a LAN.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Beginning with the Sega NetLink in 1996, Game.com in 1997 and Dreamcast in 2000, game consoles support network gaming over LANs and the Internet.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Many mobile phones and handheld consoles also offer wireless gaming with Bluetooth (or similar) technology.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] By the early 2010s online gaming had become a mainstay of console platforms such as Xbox and PlayStation.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] During the 2010s, as the number of Internet users increased, two new video game genres rapidly gained worldwide popularity – multiplayer online battle arena and battle royale game, both designed exclusively for multiplayer gameplay over the Internet.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Over time the number of people playing video games has increased.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In 2020, the majority of households in the United States have an occupant that plays video games, and 65% of gamers play multiplayer games with others either online or in person.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] For some games, "multiplayer" implies that players are playing on the same gaming system or network.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This applies to all arcade games, but also to a number of console, and personal computer games too.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Turn-based games such as chess also lend themselves to single system single screen and even to a single controller.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Multiple types of games allow players to use local multiplayer.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The term "local co-op" or "couch co-op" refers to local multiplayer games played in a cooperative manner on the same system; these may use split-screen or some other display method.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Hot-seat games are typically turn-based games with only one controller or input set – such as a single keyboard/mouse on the system.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Players rotate using the input device to perform their turn such that each is taking a turn on the "hot-seat".
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Not all local multiplayer games are played on the same console or personal computer.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Some local multiplayer games are played over a LAN.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This involves multiple devices using one local network to play together.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer games on LAN eliminate common problems faced when playing online such as lag and anonymity.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Games played on a LAN network are the focus of LAN parties.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] While local co-op and LAN parties still take place, there has been a decrease in both due to an increasing number of players and games utilizing online multiplayer gaming.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Online multiplayer games connect players over a wide area network (a common example being the Internet).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Unlike local multiplayer, players playing online multiplayer are not restricted to the same local network.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This allows players to interact with others from a much greater distance.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Playing multiplayer online offers the benefits of distance, but it also comes with its own unique challenges.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Gamers refer to latency using the term "ping", after a utility which measures round-trip network communication delays (by the use of ICMP packets).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] A player on a DSL connection with a 50-ms ping can react faster than a modem user with a 350-ms average latency.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Other problems include packet loss and choke, which can prevent a player from "registering" their actions with a server.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In first-person shooters, this problem appears when bullets hit the enemy without damage.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] The player's connection is not the only factor; some servers are slower than others.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] A server that is geographically closer to the player's connection will often provide a lower ping.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Data packets travel faster to a location that is closer to them.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] How far the device is from an internet connection (router) can also affect latency.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Asymmetrical multiplayer is a type of gameplay in which players can have significantly different roles or abilities from each other – enough to provide a significantly different experience of the game.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] A first-person shooter that adopts the asymmetrical multiplayer system is Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Giving players their own special operator changes every player's experience.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This puts an emphasis on players improvising their own game plan given the abilities their character has.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In games with stronger elements of asymmetry, one player/team may have one gameplay experience (or be in softly asymmetric roles) while the other player or team play in a drastically different way, with different mechanics, a different type of objective, or both.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Examples of games with strong asymmetry include *Dead by Daylight*, *Evolve*, and *Left 4 Dead*.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Deathloop featured opt‑in asymmetric PvP and Elden Ring’s evolved Souls invasions at scale.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Depending on the game, objectives and story, the invading player(s) goals, roles, and own objectives will be different.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Asynchronous multiplayer is a form of multiplayer gameplay where players are not necessarily playing at the same time.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This form of multiplayer game has its origins in play-by-mail games, where players would send their moves through postal mail to a game master, who then would compile and send out results for the next turn.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-mail games transitioned to electronic form as play-by-email games.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Similar games were developed for bulletin board systems, such as *Trade Wars*, where the turn structure may not be as rigorous and allow players to take actions at any time in a persistence space alongside all other players, a concept known as sporadic play.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] These types of asynchronous multiplayer games waned with the widespread availability of the Internet which allowed players to play against each other simultaneously, but remains an option in many strategy-related games, such as the *Civilization* series.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Coordination of turns are subsequently managed by one computer or a centralized server.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Further, many mobile games are based on sporadic play and use social interactions with other players, lacking direct player versus player game modes but allowing players to influence other players' games, coordinated through central game servers, another facet of asynchronous play.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Online cheating (in gaming) usually refers to modifying the game experience to give one player an advantage over others, such as using an "aimbot" – a program which automatically locks the player's crosshairs onto a target – in shooting games.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] This is also known as "hacking" or "glitching" ("glitching" refers to using a glitch, or a mistake in the code of a game, whereas "hacking" is manipulating the code of a game).
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] Cheating in video games is often done via a third-party program that modifies the game's code at runtime to give one or more players an advantage.
[src:rollback-netcode/multiplayer-video-game] In other situations, it is frequently done by changing the game's files to change the game's mechanics.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Players often blame "bad netcode" when they experience lag or reverse state transitions when synchronization between players is lost.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Although these events are sometimes caused by bugs, other networking-related causes include high latency between server and client, packet loss, or network congestion.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Depending on the game implementation, these issues can also be caused by non-network factors such as frame rendering time or inconsistent frame rate.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Netcode is often designed to mask networking irregularities and create a synchronous and smooth gamestate across multiple users.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] There are two main resolutions to this conflict implemented in modern games: delay-based and rollback-based resolution.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] The classic solution to this problem is the use of a delay-based netcode.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] When the inputs of a remote player arrive late, the game delays the inputs of the local player accordingly to synchronize the two inputs and run them simultaneously.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This added delay can be disruptive for players (especially when latency is high), but overall the change is not very noticeable.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] However, these delays can be inconsistent due to sudden fluctuations in current latency.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Should the latency between players exceed an established buffer window for the remote player, the game must wait, causing the screens to "freeze".
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This occurs because a delay-based netcode does not allow the simulation to continue until it receives the inputs from all the players in the frame in question.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This variable delay causes an inconsistent and unresponsive experience compared to offline play (or to a LAN game), and can negatively affect player performance in timing-sensitive and fast-paced genres such as fighting games.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] An alternative system to the previous netcode is rollback netcode.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Some games utilize a hybrid solution in order to disguise these "jumps" (which can become problematic as latency between players grows, as there is less and less time to react to other players' actions) with a fixed input delay and then rollback being used.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Rollback is quite effective at concealing lag spikes or other issues related to inconsistencies in the users' connections, as predictions are often correct and players do not even notice.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Nevertheless, this system can be troublesome whenever a client's game slows down (usually due to overheating), since rift problems can be caused leading to an exchange of tickets between machines at unequal rates.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This generates visual glitches that interrupt the gameplay of those players that receive inputs at a slower pace, while the player whose game is slowed down will have an advantage over the rest by receiving inputs from others at a normal rate (this is known as one-sided rollback).
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] There is a popular MIT-licensed library named GGPO designed to help implement rollback networking to games (mainly fighting games).
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Latency is unavoidable in online games, and the quality of the player's experience is strictly tied to this (the more latency there is between players, the greater the feeling that the game is not responsive to their inputs).
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] The latency of the players' network (which is largely out of a game's control) is not the only factor in question, but also the latency inherent in the way the game simulations are run.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] There are several lag compensation methods used to disguise or cope with latency (especially with high latency values).
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] A single update of a game simulation is known as a tick.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] The rate at which the simulation is run on a server is often referred to as the server's tickrate; this is essentially the server equivalent of a client's frame rate, absent any rendering system.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Tickrate is limited by the length of time it takes to run the simulation, and is often intentionally limited further to reduce instability introduced by a fluctuating tickrate, and to reduce CPU and data transmission costs.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] A lower tickrate increases latency in the synchronization of the game simulation between the server and clients.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] A lower tickrate also naturally reduces the precision of the simulation, which itself might cause problems if taken too far, or if the client and server simulations are running at significantly different rates.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Because of limitations in the amount of available bandwidth and the CPU time that's taken by network communication, some games prioritize certain vital communications while limiting the frequency and priority of less important information.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] As with tickrate, this effectively increases synchronization latency.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Game engines may limit the number of times that updates (of a simulation) are sent to a particular client and/or particular objects in the game's world in addition to reducing the precision of some values sent over the network to help with bandwidth use.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This lack of precision may in some instances be noticeable.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] Various simulation synchronization errors between machines can also fall under the "netcode issues" blanket.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] These may include bugs which cause the simulation to proceed differently on one machine than on another, or which cause some things to not be communicated when the user perceives that they ought to be.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] A game's choice of transport layer protocol (and its management and coding) can also affect perceived networking issues.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] If a game uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), there will be increased latency between players.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This protocol is based on the connection between two machines, in which they can exchange data and read it.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] These types of connections are very reliable, stable, ordered and easy to implement.
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] This type of protocol also tends to respond very slowly whenever they lose a packet, or when packets arrive in an incorrect order or duplicated, which can be very detrimental to a real-time online game (this protocol was not designed for this type of software).
[src:rollback-netcode/netcode] If the game instead uses a User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the connection between machines will be very fast, because instead of establishing a connection between them the data will be sent and received directly.
